    "what_description": "Geum paradoxum is a perennial herbaceous plant belonging to the family Rosaceae. It has a taproot system and erect stems that grow up to 50 cm in height, bearing pinnate leaves with 5-9 leaflets. The plant produces white to pink flowers in late spring, arranged in a corymb, with 5 petals and a prominent cluster of stamens. The flowers are followed by red to purple, pubescent fruits, containing 2-4 seeds each, which are dispersed by wind. Geum paradoxum is native to the mountainous regions of Europe, where it typically grows in damp meadows and rocky outcrops.",
