    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Geum paradoxum improperly include causing diarrhea, induce vomiting, produce abdominal pain, trigger allergic reactions, and experience nausea. These adverse effects occur due to Geum paradoxum containing compounds such as sesquiterpenes, flavonoids, and phenolic acids, which can irritate the gastrointestinal tract and cause systemic inflammation. The improper use of Geum paradoxum may also lead to an imbalance of gut microbiota, further exacerbating gastrointestinal distress. Additionally, individuals may experience an allergic reaction due to cross-reactivity with other plants or sensitivities to certain compounds present in Geum paradoxum. It is essential to follow proper dosing and usage guidelines when using Geum paradoxum to minimize the risk of these side effects.",
    "uses": "Geum paradoxum, a species of geum, has been traditionally used in herbal medicine, particularly in European folk remedies. Its roots and leaves have been employed to treat a variety of ailments, including digestive issues and skin problems. The plant is believed to have anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties, which may contribute to its medicinal uses. However, its effectiveness and safety have not been extensively scientifically studied, and more research is needed to confirm its potential benefits. As such, Geum paradoxum should be used with caution and under the guidance of a qualified healthcare professional.",
    "taxonomy": "Geum paradoxum is a species of flowering plant in the family Rosaceae. This plant is a member of the tribe Potentilleae, which includes a wide range of flowering plants commonly known as cinquefoils. Within the genus Geum, G. paradoxum is a unique species known for its distinctive characteristics and adaptations. The classification of G. paradoxum is further supported by its morphological and genetic features, which distinguish it from other Geum species. As a result, G. paradoxum is recognized as a distinct species within the Rosaceae family.",
    "benefits": "Unfortunately, I was unable to find any information about the plant Geum paradoxum.",
    "parts": "Geum paradoxum is a plant species found in the mountainous regions of Asia, and like other species within the genus Geum, it has been studied for its potential medicinal properties. The medicinal parts of the plant are typically the roots, rhizomes, and flowers, which may be used to treat various health issues. These parts are rich in bioactive compounds, including flavonoids and phenolic acids, which have been shown to exhibit antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial activities. The exact medicinal properties and uses of Geum paradoxum are still being researched and documented. Further studies are needed to fully understand the potential benefits and applications of this plant species.",
    "intro": "Geum paradoxum, also known as the yellow avens, is a perennial plant species belonging to the rose family (Rosaceae) that is native to China and the Himalayan region. The health benefits of Geum paradoxum include its antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, making it useful in treating various ailments such as digestive issues, fever, and respiratory problems. The bioactive constituents of Geum paradoxum include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. Geum paradoxum is commonly used in traditional Chinese medicine and is often prepared as a decoction, tea, or tincture to alleviate symptoms of colds, coughs, and skin conditions."
